sentences: Robert Wayne "Bob" Birch (July 14, 1956 – August 15, 2012) was an American musician.
One day he picked up his junior high band director Art Dries's Mosrite bass during school lunch and something about it felt totally right.
Birch played six nights a week amidst the Detroit club scene while attending classes during the day.

He arrived in Los Angeles in 1981, and struggled to make the contacts he needed, but meeting saxophonist Michael Paulo at the musician's union started things off for Birch.
His momentum continued to build as he was able to get hired for multiple recording dates.
Finally, in 1985 he was involved in a record deal with a band named Fortune.
"Stacey" made it on the Billboard Hot 100 singles list for six straight weeks.
He remained in the music scene by playing gigs every night and joining as many bands as possible.
Later in 1985, he met keyboardist Guy Babylon.
In 1988, Guy recommended Bob for Mark Ashton's band.
He set off on a world tour with Feliciano which lasted four years.
When Elton John ended his tour in 1989, Guy Babylon introduced Bob to John's longtime guitarist, Davey Johnstone.
They named their band Warpipes, and their album debuted in 1990.
On February 14, 1992, Elton agreed and asked Davey to call Bob, which began what the Detroit born bassist calls 'sideman heaven'.
In 1993, he met musician and composer Marc Bonilla and was asked to join his band, 'The Dragonchoir' for the time he had between tours with Elton.
Bonilla also gave Birch the chance to play with one of his favorite vocalists, David Coverdale, at Mark & Brian's Christmas show.

Another memorable moment for Bob was when Rick Latham, drummer and friend of Bob's, gave him the chance to play with Edgar Winter and the White Trash featuring Rick Derringer reunion at the Montreux Jazz Festival in 1999.

That led to the opportunity to co-write as well as play on a song for Joseph Williams' solo album, This Fall.
In 1995, Birch was badly injured in a car accident in which he was hit by a pick-up truck while walking the streets of Montreal with his fellow band members.
The doctors initially told him that he would never walk again, but within six months he was back on tour with Elton John, and continued to do so for the next seventeen years.

Throughout those years, Birch struggled with constant headaches, dizziness, vertigo, and severe pain throughout his body.
During his final tour before his death, Birch was forced to perform while seated on a chair because of the pain he was enduring, which had been aggravated by a fall accident at the start of the tour.
During the last two weeks leading up to his death, Birch struggled with severe gastrointestinal issues brought on by his injury and suffered from extreme insomnia, during which he lost 23 pounds.
On August 15, 2012, he died from an apparent self-inflicted gunshot wound in his Los Angeles home, aged 56.
